It is strongly recommended that you participate in the sociology department internship program so that you can gain valuable experience and build your social network to enhance your chances of acceptance in law school. It is important to participate in an internship during your undergraduate career so that it can help you decide if this is really what you want to do with your life. We have outstanding internships available in civil, family, or criminal law. These internships earn 3 credit hours to count towards your major or minor requirements and for sociology majors, they may qualify for writing intensive credit. To be eligible, you must be a sociology major or minor,and have a 3.0 GPR (or near). For more information or to apply, contact Dr. Dietrich at socintern@tamu.edu."}

It's interesting that the author of this essay appears to presume that STEM disciplines don't develop \"critical thinking.\"  I know a number of scientists and engineers who would vigorously disagree. Perhaps a better solution is a core undergraduate curriculum that includes both STEM and the humanities. Speaking for myself, I  never took \"cowboy\" classes, instead grinding through the same chemistry, physics, and calculus as science and technology majors.  The perspective I gained from that coursework has been a tremendous asset during my career. Education isn't an either/or proposition.", "id": "10151746020197320_27089361", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"name": "Laura Chatham Mrachek", "id": "638507389"}, "like_count": 4, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2013-07-29T18:47:02+0000", "message": "I believe a Liberal Arts education is important for just the reasons cited in the article. However, I also believe that Liberal Arts students must be equipped to succeed in a world that increasingly values degrees that easily transition into careers (engineering, nursing, etc.). I attended a small, academically rigorous liberal arts college that has produced 26 Rhodes Scholars and dozens of Fulbright Scholars. The college has an excellent record of preparing its students for graduate and professional schools, but for those who wanted to enter the working world after receiving a bachelor's degree, achieving immediate career success was a challenge. For example, a friend who graduated with a Philosophy degree ended up selling Goodyear tires for a living. I am thankful that A&M's School of Liberal Arts puts an emphasis on training and experiences that enhance one's marketability upon graduation. For example, INTS majors, such as my daughter, are required to become proficient in a foreign language and are encouraged to master one of the three critical foreign languages -- Arabic, Russian, and Chinese -- that are most desired by corporations, governmental agencies, etc. In addition, travel abroad experiences are required for INTS majors and highly encouraged for other majors, and the Public Policy Internship Program offers a chance to gain valuable work experience before graduation. Kudos to A&M for giving its students a valuable Liberal Arts education AND equipping them for their future careers!", "id": "10151746020197320_27089474", "user_likes": false}]}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/93033712319/posts/10151746020197320", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/93033712319/posts/10151746020197320", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2013-07-29T18:47:02+0000", "caption": "www.huffingtonpost.com", "application": {"name": "HootSuite", "id": "183319479511"}, "link": "http://ow.ly/nm9LV", "shares": {"count": 4}, "created_time": "2013-07-29T18:21:10+0000", "message": "The Huffington Post wrote about the importance of a Liberal Arts education in today's global marketplace.
